Setting Up: Billboard music data

Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(psych)
library(scales)
library(forcats)
library(viridis)

Data

For this section you will be using Billboard music data from TidyTuesday. See https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/tree/master/data/2021/2021-09-14 for more detailed information about the dataset.

set.seed(8765)
billboard <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2021/2021-09-14/audio_features.csv') %>% sample_n(5000)

Correlation 1

Exercise 1 -

Use the cor.test() function to run a correlation. Select any two numeric variables of interest for your correlation. Interpret the output in terms of significance and direction.

cor.test(billboard$spotify_track_duration_ms,
         billboard$spotify_track_popularity)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  billboard$spotify_track_duration_ms and billboard$spotify_track_popularity
## t = 10.871, df = 4147, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1367243 0.1958990
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1664615

There is a small, significant (p < 0.05) positive correlation between track popularity and track duration.

Exercise 2 -

Create a ggplot scatterplot visualization of the two variables you selected for the correlation. Add a geom_smooth regression “lm” line to the plot. Interpret what you see. Make sure you clean up the labels and add a theme.

ggplot(billboard, aes(spotify_track_duration_ms,
                  spotify_track_popularity)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x = "Song Length (ms)", y = "Song Popularity")

While it is positive, we see most of the song length clustering is around 250000 ms.

Correlation 2

Exercise 3 -

Use the cor.test() function to run a different correlation. Select any two numeric variables of interest (different from exercise 1) for your correlation. Interpret the output in terms of significance and direction.

cor.test(billboard$energy, billboard$loudness)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  billboard$energy and billboard$loudness
## t = 61.435, df = 4133, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6746030 0.7064815
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.6908779

There is a strong positive and significant (p < 0.05) correlation between the energy and loudness of a song.

Exercise 4 -

Create a ggplot scatterplot visualization of the two variables you selected for the previous correlation. Add a geom_smooth regression “lm” line to the plot. Interpret what you see. Make sure you clean up the labels and add a theme.

ggplot(billboard, aes(energy, loudness)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x = "Song Energy", y = "Song Loudness")

Similar to the correlation output, we see a strong positive linear relationship between the two variables.

Correlation 3

Exercise 5 -

Use the cor.test() function to run a different correlation. Select any two numeric variables of interest (different from exercise 1 & 3) for your correlation. Interpret the output in terms of significance and direction.

cor.test(billboard$instrumentalness, billboard$valence)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  billboard$instrumentalness and billboard$valence
## t = 3.3479, df = 4133, p-value = 0.0008215
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.02155890 0.08235676
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## 0.05200602

There is a weak positive significant correlation between the valence and intrumentalness of a song.

Exercise 6 -

Create a ggplot scatterplot visualization of the two variables you selected for the previous correlation. Add a geom_smooth regression “lm” line to the plot. Interpret what you see. Make sure you clean up the labels and add a theme.

ggplot(billboard, aes(instrumentalness, valence)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x = "Song Instrumentalness", y = "Song Valence")

The intrumentalness score have a strong cluster around 0.

Correlation 4

Exercise 7 -

Use the cor.test() function to run a different correlation. Select any two numeric variables of interest (different from exercise 1 & 3 & 5) for your correlation. Interpret the output in terms of significance and direction.

cor.test(billboard$tempo, billboard$energy)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  billboard$tempo and billboard$energy
## t = 10.532, df = 4133, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1318425 0.1912131
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1616741

There is a small positive significant relationship between the tempo and energy of a song.

Exercise 8 -

Create a ggplot scatterplot visualization of the two variables you selected for the previous correlation. Add a geom_smooth regression “lm” line to the plot. Interpret what you see. Make sure you clean up the labels and add a theme.

ggplot(billboard, aes(tempo, energy)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x = "Song Tempo", y = "Song Energy")

While there is a big circular cluster in the middle, we do still see a slight positive trend happening between the two variables.
